          "Higher Education",
          "E-Learning",
          "49 undergraduate students",
          "1 Instructional Technologies course",
          "Questionnaires, LMS logs",
          "None Specified",
          "[Transitions between behavioral codes]",
          "Data was collected and aggregated continuously.\n\nStudy also includes separation between control group and a grooup that receives feedback at specific moments in time.",
          "Markov Chain",
          "-",
          "9",
          "Combinations of transitions between 3 groups at 3 moments in time throughout the course duration:\n\ne.g.: \nT1I→T2I→T3I → Intense on all 3 moments of measurement",
          "Engagement levels are likely to increase over time. \n\nAbility to transition from not engaged to an engaged state represents an important predictor of final performance. \n\nLearners who are light or transition to a Light state are more likely to need intense feedback.",
          "Being willing to fully participate in the course was a mandatory requirement to participate in the study.\n\nDifferences between control group and experimental group are measured using ANCOVA tests.\n\nNo differences between groups on academic achievement or affective engagement. ",
          "Small sample size, with selection bias.\n\nEthical considerations between a group that receives feedback while another does not.\n\nUndisclosed criteria for selection of clusters.\n\nSpecific to online contexts.\n\nLag-Sequential Analysis may lose resolution in the context of a 14-week course being analyzed as whole and may benefit with its application on a smaller subset of events. "
        ]
